	"keywords": "Accessibility, Web Development, Tech, UX, Design",
	"description": "It’s easy to think about a layout as being a primarily visual concern. The\nheader goes up top, the sidebar is over here, the call to action is in an\noverlay on top of the content (just kidding). Grids, borders, spacing and color\nall portray valuable visual data, but if these hints to the structure of a page\nare only visible, some users may find your content unintelligible.\n\nYou can experience this first hand if you try using a screen reader on the web.\nWhen I fired up VoiceOver on my Mac and too",
	"headline": "How to design website layouts for screen readers",
